WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.880
 So now we're going to dive into the notion of abstractions.

00:00:02.880 --> 00:00:06.000
 We're going to take an interface and kind of compare it

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:10.880
 across a number of different languages. We're going to call this abstraction a map.

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:17.280
 A map is a common term that we use kind of abstractly to describe key value collections.

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:20.320
 And each different language tends to have a different name for that.

00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:24.240
 C++, they actually call it a map. Python calls it a dictionary.

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:26.800
 Java also calls it a map, but with an uppercase.

00:00:26.800 --> 00:00:30.720
 And in PHP, we call it arrays. And in JavaScript, they're actually objects.

00:00:30.720 --> 00:00:34.080
 And then we're going to look at the iterator pattern

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:37.920
 as an abstraction for looping across multiple implementations.

00:00:37.920 --> 00:00:43.280
 So let's take a look at some sample Python code that's playing with a dictionary class.

00:00:43.280 --> 00:00:45.280
 So we created a dictionary at the very beginning.

00:00:45.280 --> 00:00:49.680
 Then we filled it up with some key value pairs.

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:53.440
 And so you'll notice that like D sub z equals 8 and D sub z equals 1.

00:00:53.440 --> 00:00:58.960
 That's got to be a replacement. So there's no 8 in there after that second replacement.

00:00:58.960 --> 00:01:03.760
 We then print it. Then we do a get of z to see if it's there.

00:01:03.760 --> 00:01:08.720
 And then we do a get of x, and it's not there. So we see x equals 42 when it executes.

00:01:08.720 --> 00:01:13.600
 Then we say, give me an iterator of the items in this dictionary.

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:19.680
 And so what that basically is going to do is the iterator itself is not a list.

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:23.920
 In earlier versions, like Python 2, when you asked for the items, you tended to get

00:01:23.920 --> 00:01:27.200
 a fully filled out list. But that's a waste of memory.

00:01:27.200 --> 00:01:33.280
 So the iterator is simply a data structure that is keeping track of where in the list we are.

00:01:33.280 --> 00:01:38.080
 And then we call it next over and over and over to advance through the iterator.

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:41.120
 So we don't have to make a complete copy of all the data.

00:01:41.120 --> 00:01:44.240
 We just have a little pointer that advances through.

00:01:44.240 --> 00:01:48.000
 So items is a relatively small data structure.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.040
 I mean, it doesn't include all the data in the dictionary.

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:55.680
 It just is itself a pointer to something. It's all internal.

00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:59.120
 Remember, abstraction is like, hey, I can give you the next thing.

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:03.920
 Internally, there's pointers and all kinds of crazy things inside these iterators,

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:05.120
 which we shall soon see.

00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:10.800
 So if you print out items, you will see that it's like an item iterator for dictionaries.

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:14.160
 That's what that class dict item iterator is telling us.

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:19.360
 But then we can call the next function, which is built into Python, and say, hey, iterator,

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:23.600
 do your job and hand me back the next thing.

00:02:23.600 --> 00:02:28.480
 Or if we reach the end of the dictionary, false.

00:02:28.480 --> 00:02:31.280
 Now, if you come in any order, these have any order dictionaries, of course.

00:02:31.280 --> 00:02:34.800
 But we get back the entry or we get back false.

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:39.760
 So we say, while entry, then we print the entry.

00:02:39.760 --> 00:02:42.560
 And then we say, hey, give me the next one.

00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:44.160
 And then loop up to the top.

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:46.320
 And when it becomes false, we're all done.

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:49.120
 And so what you see, because this is an order dictionary,

00:02:49.120 --> 00:02:54.000
 is you see z1, x9, b3, a4, and then it finishes.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:58.240
 So we don't know about next, arrow next.

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:02.080
 We don't know even the-- in this case, we're just getting a tuple back.

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:03.120
 So we do know that.

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:07.680
 But if we take a look at the same kind of concept in PHP,

00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:10.640
 we make an array and we fill it up.

00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:13.760
 z gets to be 8, z gets to be 1.

00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:14.880
 And that's an overwrite.

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:17.440
 And then we put three more things in.

00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:18.800
 And we can print them out.

00:03:18.800 --> 00:03:22.240
 We see that it's kind of an order dictionary, as it were.

00:03:22.240 --> 00:03:25.040
 x, z, y, b, a.

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:27.120
 And then we do a get.

00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:31.520
 And we're using the null coalesce operator, which is the double question mark.

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:34.800
 So we say, give me a sub z.

00:03:34.800 --> 00:03:37.440
 And if that doesn't exist, then give me back 42.

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:38.560
 So it's kind of like a get.

00:03:38.560 --> 00:03:41.680
 But that's a PHP 7 and later.

00:03:41.680 --> 00:03:44.160
 So we look up x, and we don't get it.

00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:45.680
 So we see x equals 42.

00:03:45.680 --> 00:03:48.160
 And then we run through an iterator.

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:51.520
 And again, there are structures inside of arrays.

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:55.360
 But we know nothing about how PHP implemented the arrays.

00:03:55.360 --> 00:04:00.880
 We just know that if we say, for each a, as key is assigned a value,

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:02.160
 we can print out k and v.

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:07.680
 And so this is a very abstract way of saying, I want to go through all of them.

00:04:07.680 --> 00:04:09.520
 I want the keys and values.

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:10.480
 Give those back to me.

00:04:10.480 --> 00:04:14.800
 But I don't care how you do it, whether you make extra copies of data, et cetera.

00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:17.280
 So that's another iterator pattern.

00:04:17.280 --> 00:04:20.560
 Now, in C, the data structure we create is a map.

00:04:20.560 --> 00:04:24.960
 And if you read this, you'll see that it talks about how the implementations work,

00:04:24.960 --> 00:04:26.880
 et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:32.480
 But the C++ equivalent of a dictionary is, in effect, a map.

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:35.200
 And so this is some C++ code.

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:38.160
 The first thing we see is we're going to create a map.

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:40.800
 And in this less than, greater than syntax,

00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:45.120
 you're seeing that the map is mapping a string to an integer.

00:04:45.120 --> 00:04:47.360
 So the key, in this case, is a string.

00:04:47.360 --> 00:04:48.960
 And the value is an integer.

00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:54.160
 The previous two languages didn't care so much about types.

00:04:54.160 --> 00:04:59.840
 And so that's why they-- but now we're in C++, which cares greatly about types.

00:04:59.840 --> 00:05:02.720
 And so now we say mp sub z equals 8.

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:06.800
 Then mp sub z equals 1, which, again, is a replace operator.

00:05:06.800 --> 00:05:10.480
 Then y, b, and a are set to 2, 3, and 4, respectively.

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:15.120
 And then we do like a get operation.

00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:19.120
 And this one is a little funky in C.

00:05:19.120 --> 00:05:22.800
 Why they didn't give us a get operation, I do not know.

00:05:22.800 --> 00:05:26.720
 But what this is using as a ternary operation is saying mp count.

00:05:26.720 --> 00:05:30.320
 How many z keys are inside this thing?

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:32.720
 And if it's greater than 0, we print out mp sub z.

00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:37.280
 And if it's not greater than 0-- if it's 0, then we print out 42,

00:05:37.280 --> 00:05:41.440
 which functions like a Python get on a dictionary.

00:05:41.440 --> 00:05:42.800
 So this syntax is funky.

00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:43.920
 You can go like Google it.

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:47.440
 It's like there's two ways you can do it.

00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:49.840
 And neither of them makes me particularly happy.

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:52.240
 Because I think that for a map-like object,

00:05:52.240 --> 00:05:56.480
 a get with a default is pretty valuable.

00:05:57.520 --> 00:06:02.640
 The notion of running through and counting means you found it or didn't find it.

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:04.400
 And if you found it, why don't you give it back to me?

00:06:04.400 --> 00:06:06.240
 But they just don't have a get.

00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:09.760
 But now we see an iteration.

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:11.040
 So it says for auto.

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:14.240
 Auto is a type, but it's an automatic type.

00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:21.120
 And it knows that this mp is a map string int.

00:06:21.120 --> 00:06:25.280
 And so it creates this current pointer, which is a pointer to--

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:28.400
 not exactly a map string, it's a map entry.

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:29.840
 But we don't care about that.

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:31.040
 There's actually a type.

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:33.520
 Curr, the variable curr, has a type.

00:06:33.520 --> 00:06:37.040
 Whatever the mp begin is going to give us back as a type.

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:39.360
 And it knows that based on map string int.

00:06:39.360 --> 00:06:41.440
 And it makes curr the right type.

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:43.280
 So this is like whatever type you want.

00:06:43.280 --> 00:06:45.040
 But it is not any type.

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:46.560
 It's a very precise type.

00:06:46.560 --> 00:06:52.320
 And that's a sort of a hallmark of C++, is all the types are very, very precise.

00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:53.200
 So it's a for loop.

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:54.960
 You see the three semicolons?

00:06:54.960 --> 00:07:03.200
 The initialization clause, auto curr equals mp begin, says, hey, we've got our iterator.

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:04.080
 Get me started.

00:07:04.080 --> 00:07:05.280
 Begin.

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:06.640
 Go to the beginning of it.

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:07.840
 And give me the first one.

00:07:07.840 --> 00:07:14.480
 And as long as curr is not equal to mp end, there are no more.

00:07:14.480 --> 00:07:15.840
 That's kind of like their null.

00:07:15.840 --> 00:07:18.160
 And then plus plus curr.

00:07:18.160 --> 00:07:20.240
 So we're incrementing curr.

00:07:20.240 --> 00:07:22.320
 And then there's a key and a value.

00:07:22.320 --> 00:07:23.760
 And they don't call them key and value.

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:25.680
 They call them first and second.

00:07:25.680 --> 00:07:31.280
 That's the thing coming back from mp begin has an attribute first and an attribute second.

00:07:31.280 --> 00:07:34.960
 And we call the c_str to convert that to a C string.

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:36.240
 So I can use printf.

00:07:36.240 --> 00:07:38.080
 So I don't have to use cout.

00:07:38.080 --> 00:07:39.440
 Just because I don't know why.

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:41.120
 I didn't want to use cout in this one.

00:07:41.120 --> 00:07:46.320
 But you see an abstraction where the first and the second are known.

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:49.680
 But because this is a key and a value, it's not such a big deal.

00:07:49.680 --> 00:07:52.880
 And so that's doing the same thing in C++.

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:56.960
 In Java, they have an interface.

00:07:56.960 --> 00:07:58.960
 And you see the word interface here.

00:07:58.960 --> 00:08:04.320
 An interface named map less than greater than k comma v.

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:10.400
 And just like in C++, this is saying a map is a key and a value.

00:08:10.400 --> 00:08:14.000
 But what we're putting in here is the type of the key and the type of the value.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:18.400
 So we're going to make a map that has a string key and an integer value.

00:08:18.400 --> 00:08:20.160
 You might say why didn't I do string string?

00:08:20.160 --> 00:08:24.000
 And that's because it makes it just easier when I'm writing so much C code.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.240
 It also will be fun when we actually count things, if you remember.

00:08:28.240 --> 00:08:30.480
 From a long time ago, we did count it.

00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:32.320
 But map is the class.

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:37.360
 And string integer, this is kind of polymorphism where it can be a map.

00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:42.000
 It maps strings to integers, or integers to strings, or strings to strings,

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.480
 or who knows what to who knows what else.

00:08:44.480 --> 00:08:47.360
 Meaning this map is exceedingly flexible.

00:08:47.360 --> 00:08:49.760
 And it doesn't care what kind of type it's using.

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:52.560
 As long as the type meets some basic criteria.

00:08:52.560 --> 00:08:56.960
 So here's a bit of Java code that does the same thing that we've been doing.

00:08:56.960 --> 00:09:01.200
 And so we see that we're going to make this variable map, lowercase,

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:04.720
 is of type map, map of strings to integers.

00:09:04.720 --> 00:09:08.480
 And we're going to create a new tree map of strings to integers.

00:09:08.480 --> 00:09:10.320
 And the new creates a new object.

00:09:10.320 --> 00:09:15.520
 Now the difference between a map and a tree map is a map is an interface

00:09:15.520 --> 00:09:17.760
 and a tree map is an implementation.

00:09:17.760 --> 00:09:21.040
 The tree map says we're going to build this key value store,

00:09:21.040 --> 00:09:22.720
 but we're going to store our data in a tree.

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:25.600
 And that says to a computer scientist

00:09:25.600 --> 00:09:29.520
 that it's going to have a certain performance and memory footprint.

00:09:29.520 --> 00:09:32.320
 Trees are a great way to store key value data.

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:38.480
 But they take a little bit more memory than a linked list, as we will later see.

00:09:38.480 --> 00:09:42.240
 And so we're choosing an implementation.

00:09:42.240 --> 00:09:46.240
 The other thing where it says tree map that you might use is what's called a hash map.

00:09:46.240 --> 00:09:51.280
 Which is a simpler map implementation, but doesn't keep things in order.

00:09:51.280 --> 00:09:52.640
 So you can choose.

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:57.680
 The map doesn't change, but you can say I'd like this to be a tree map or a hash map.

00:09:57.680 --> 00:09:59.600
 They're both key value stores.

00:09:59.600 --> 00:10:05.040
 One is an ordered key value store and a hash map is an unordered key value store.

00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:11.120
 And they both have different performance behaviors and internal implementation details.

00:10:11.120 --> 00:10:14.320
 But it doesn't matter because they're both maps.

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:18.240
 In this code that we write, we could literally change tree map to hash map

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:20.240
 and the code will work exactly the same.

00:10:20.240 --> 00:10:23.040
 But the order of the key value pairs might be a little bit different.

00:10:23.040 --> 00:10:30.240
 Now you'll notice that when we're putting stuff in, we call a method, map.put.

00:10:30.240 --> 00:10:36.960
 So everything we've seen so far says like map open bracket quote z quote close bracket equals 8.

00:10:36.960 --> 00:10:40.880
 Java chose not to do what's called operator overloading.

00:10:40.880 --> 00:10:43.440
 And so it really does everything in a method.

00:10:43.440 --> 00:10:47.040
 So the kind of things that you think are going to be done with an assignment statement

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:50.400
 or some other syntax tend to be done.

00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:56.880
 It's like, OK, we're going to do everything with methods and parameters.

00:10:56.880 --> 00:11:00.560
 Now map is the object instance that's being worked on.

00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:05.440
 And z, that's basically saying map sub z equals 8.

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:08.640
 And we'll do in a put of z of 1, which is going to overwrite.

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:10.880
 You'll see I'm doing the same thing in each one of these things.

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:14.480
 And then put in y, b, and a with 2, 3, and 4 respectively.

00:11:14.480 --> 00:11:15.360
 I can print it out.

00:11:15.360 --> 00:11:20.080
 And if you look at the printout, it looks a lot like what it looks like in Python.

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:24.320
 There's this thing called get or default, map.get or default,

00:11:24.320 --> 00:11:28.960
 which is if the key z is in there, give it to the value.

00:11:28.960 --> 00:11:30.880
 Or just give me 42 as a default.

00:11:30.880 --> 00:11:32.400
 And in the first case, z is there.

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:33.840
 In the second case, x is not there.

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:35.360
 So you see x is 42.

00:11:35.360 --> 00:11:36.560
 That's not a bad name for it.

00:11:36.560 --> 00:11:38.560
 It's a little more verbose than get.

00:11:38.560 --> 00:11:41.440
 It's pretty much the same as what we do in Python.

00:11:41.440 --> 00:11:43.200
 And then we have an iterator.

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:48.880
 And now you see in this for loop, you see kind of the notion of the fact

00:11:48.880 --> 00:11:53.840
 that the iteration variable has a type.

00:11:53.840 --> 00:11:55.040
 So we don't have this auto.

00:11:55.040 --> 00:11:56.720
 Later versions of Java may have an auto.

00:11:56.720 --> 00:11:58.880
 But now I'm explicitly showing you.

00:11:58.880 --> 00:12:01.120
 It's not a map string integer.

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:04.080
 It's a map.entry, which is an entry inside of a map.

00:12:04.080 --> 00:12:09.280
 It's an abstract interface to the entry inside of a map.

00:12:09.280 --> 00:12:12.720
 Each entry that's got to match the string integer that's in the map.

00:12:12.720 --> 00:12:15.280
 And so there's a map string integer, which is the whole map.

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:18.240
 And then there's a map entry, which is one of the entries.

00:12:18.240 --> 00:12:22.480
 But this map entry is also kind of an iterator, right?

00:12:22.480 --> 00:12:25.040
 So we're going to iterate and move forward.

00:12:25.040 --> 00:12:26.640
 So it's not just the key and the value.

00:12:26.640 --> 00:12:28.800
 It's really the key and the value and the position.

00:12:28.800 --> 00:12:30.880
 But we don't see the position.

00:12:30.880 --> 00:12:38.560
 All we know is we use this for syntax, which is kind of like a for in in Python.

00:12:38.560 --> 00:12:43.680
 And we call map.entry set, which is I want a set of all the entries.

00:12:43.680 --> 00:12:47.840
 And that map entry set does not construct a giant in memory list

00:12:47.840 --> 00:12:49.840
 and then go through it.

00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:54.800
 That actually creates a single map entry with the key and the value of the first one.

00:12:54.800 --> 00:12:56.080
 And then you hit it again.

00:12:56.080 --> 00:12:57.120
 And it gives you the second one.

00:12:57.120 --> 00:12:57.680
 You hit it again.

00:12:57.680 --> 00:12:58.560
 It gives the third one.

00:12:58.560 --> 00:13:00.560
 And pretty soon it gives you null.

00:13:00.560 --> 00:13:02.160
 Which means that the loop is going to stop.

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:06.160
 And the entry itself does have a key and a value.

00:13:06.160 --> 00:13:10.160
 Now, key and value are known in the map entry interface.

00:13:10.160 --> 00:13:13.680
 So you say entry.getKey and entry.getValue.

00:13:13.680 --> 00:13:18.880
 Now, they're using methods to give us back the key and the value

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:23.760
 versus in previous things you saw attributes being used in the iterators.

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:30.400
 And that's because Java is obsessed with preferring to use accessor methods

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:34.640
 like getters and setters versus just grabbing attributes.

00:13:34.640 --> 00:13:38.560
 And the key thing is they can add just a little bit of business logic if they want

00:13:38.560 --> 00:13:41.200
 rather than having to do something and have the key and the value

00:13:41.200 --> 00:13:44.880
 already completely computed sitting in an attribute for you to use.

00:13:44.880 --> 00:13:49.200
 Entry.getKey, sometimes it just grabs something that's already got computed

00:13:49.200 --> 00:13:51.520
 or it might actually go do something or do some work.

00:13:51.520 --> 00:13:56.000
 And so by putting these things in what Java calls getters and setters,

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:59.200
 in this case we're not seeing a setter so much.

00:14:00.800 --> 00:14:04.080
 But making it so that instead of it being entry.key,

00:14:04.080 --> 00:14:06.240
 it's entry.getKey open print close print.

00:14:06.240 --> 00:14:09.840
 That's a very Java way of thinking about this.

00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:16.000
 So we started by talking about a simple Python dictionary where we fill it up,

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.560
 we use get, then we create an iterator,

00:14:18.560 --> 00:14:22.480
 and then we abstractly loop through that iterator.

00:14:22.480 --> 00:14:25.600
 And that's what we wanted to accomplish in this section

00:14:25.600 --> 00:14:29.680
 just to see how that is done in a wide range of different languages.

